**Outline: "Martin Luther King Jr.: A Legacy of Social Justice"**

I. Overview(Page 1)
A. Overview of Martin Luther King Jr.'s significance in American history
B. Thesis statement: Exploring King's life, contributions, and enduring
legacy

**II. Early Life and Education (Page 2)**
- A. Birth and family background in Atlanta, Georgia
- B. Demonstrated leadership qualities from a young age
1. Skipping ninth and twelfth grades
2. Entering Morehouse College at age 15
a. Influence of early education on future activism
b. Educational journey at Crozer Theological Seminary and Boston University

**III. Leadership in the Civil Rights Movement (Page 3)**
- A. Strategic use of nonviolent resistance
- B. Role in organizing the Montgomery Bus Boycott
1. Pivotal role in organizing protests
2. Elected president of the Montgomery Improvement Association
a. Advocacy for nonviolent protest tactics
b. Formation of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC)

**IV. March on Washington and Nobel Peace Prize (Page 4)**
- A. Significance of the "I Have a Dream" speech
- B. Recognition with the Nobel Peace Prize in 1964
1. Impact of the speech on American society
2. Youngest recipient of the Nobel Peace Prize
a. Elevating the civil rights movement on a global scale
b. Commitment to nonviolent resistance highlighted

**V. Passage of the Voting Rights Act (Page 5)**
- A. Overview and aims of the Voting Rights Act of 1965
- B. Impact on African American voting rights and civil rights movement
1. Overcoming legal barriers to African American voting rights
2. Expanding access to the ballot for millions of African Americans
a. Historical significance of the Voting Rights Act
b. Role in advancing the civil rights movement

**VI. Assassination and Legacy (Page 6)**
- A. Tragic death in Memphis, Tennessee, in 1968
- B. Enduring legacy as a champion of civil rights and social justice
1. Shockwaves felt around the world
2. Inspiring future generations to continue the fight for equality
a. Influence on subsequent social justice movements
b. Commemorating King's contributions and sacrifices

**VII. Reflection and Call to Action (Page 7)**
- A. Reflection on King's impact and significance
- B. Call to honor his memory and continue the pursuit of justice and
equality

